  "prompt": "Why does blue vitriol change its colour from blue to white on heating?",
  "response": "Blue vitriol, also known as copper(II) sulfate pentahydrate (CuSO\u2084\u00b75H\u2082O), exhibits a color change when it is heated due to the loss of its water of crystallization. At room temperature, it appears as blue crystals because the copper(II) ions in the presence of water produce a vibrant blue color.\n\nWhen heated, blue vitriol undergoes dehydration, losing its water molecules. The process can be summarized as follows:\n\n1. **Heating process**: As the temperature increases, the water molecules of crystallization are driven off, causing a phase change in the compound. \n2. **Change in color**: As the water is removed, the hydrated copper(II) sulfate changes from the blue hydrated form to an anhydrous form, which is typically a white or off-white powder. This anhydrous form is known as copper(II) sulfate or simply anhydrous copper sulfate (CuSO\u2084).\n\nThus, the blue color is directly associated with the presence of water in the crystal structure, and its absence due to heating leads to a white appearance. When exposed to moisture again, the anhydrous copper sulfate can rehydrate and regain its blue color by absorbing water from the environment.",
